Now to what's coming next. The rule engine is the platform's next core capability — applicability driven by rules, not by manual mapping. A control applies when an application meets defined conditions. These conditions use attributes the platform already gets from source systems like LeanIX — hosting type, customer-facing, SOX classification. For example, customer-facing applications classified as SOX automatically require evidence for Access Control Policy, Multi-Factor Authentication, and Security Event Logging. No one maps these manually — the rule engine sees the application's attributes and produces the right set of controls. Ownership cascades from the BU mappings we just walked through — the rule engine identifies which controls apply; the BU mapping identifies who owns each one. The Risk Manager reviews exceptions, not every row. Auditable, not asserted. Rules become the unit of governance — not records.
